ce:section.ce:para:
The PVDF/TiO2 (T1, T10, T15, T20 and T30), PVDF/TiO2(s)@CQDs (T(s)C15) and PVDF/TiO2(i)@CQDs (T(i)C15) hybrid films were prepared using ink-jet printing technology and the effect of the printing number was explored. As shown in Fig. 6
                        (a), there was less TiO2 on the film surface when the number of prints was 1 time (T1). The TiO2 loading on the T10 surface increased, but there were still uncovered areas (Fig. S3(a, c)). The TiO2 layer on the surface of T15 was dense and uniform (Fig. 6(b)), and the photocatalytic degradation efficiency (η) was maximized (discussed in detail in the subsequent “photocatalytic dye degradation” section, from which the optimal printing number of 15 times was determined). The distribution of TiO2 remained densely distributed as the printing number increased to 20 (T20) and 30 (T30) times (Fig. 6(c) and Fig. S3(b, d)). The surface EDS results of T15 further indicate the uniform and dense distribution of TiO2 on the substrate. As shown in the cross-section morphology and EDS mapping of T15 (Fig. 6(e)), TiO2 is thinly and densely loaded on the surface of the film, and a small number of nanoparticles are sprayed into the film pores. Thermogravimetric (TG) results (Fig. S4) show that the loading of the photocatalyst on the film surface was low at 0.49 wt%, which implies high catalyst utilization. The surface morphology of T(s)C15 (Fig. 6(f)) is similar to that of T15. Compared to T15 and T(s)C15, the surface of T(i)C15 is relatively smoother due to the smaller size of TiO2(i)@CQDs (Fig. 6(g)). As shown in AFM images (Fig. 7
                        ), the surface roughness of T15, T(s)C15, and T(i)C15 is 30.5, 31.7, and 23.2 nm, respectively.
